S'  We address the problem of testing whether a given dynamic graph is temporally\nconnected, {\\it i.e.} a temporal path (also called a {\\em journey}) exists\nbetween all pairs of vertices. We consider a discrete version of the problem,\nwhere the topology is given as an evolving graph\n$\\mathcal{G}=\\{G_1,G_2,...,G_{k}\\}$ whose set of vertices is invariant and the\nset of (directed) edges varies over time. Two cases are studied, depending on\nwhether a single edge or an unlimited number of edges can be crossed in a same\n$G_i$ (strict journeys {\\it vs} non-strict journeys).\n  In the case of strict journeys, two algorithms designed for other problems\ncan be adapted. However, we show that a dedicated approach performs better than\none of them in all cases, and than the other one for a large range of graphs,\nin particular those whose density is low at any time (though potentially high\nover time). The time complexity of our algorithm is $O(k\\mu n)$, where\n$k=|\\mathcal{G}|$ is the number of time steps $\\mathcal{G}$ covers and\n$\\mu=max(|E_i|)$ is the maximum {\\em instant} density, to be contrasted with\n$m=|\\cup E_i|$, the {\\em cumulated} density. Indeed, it is not uncommon for a\nmobility scenario to satisfy, for instance, both $\\mu=o(n)$ and\n$m=\\Theta(n^2)$. We characterize the key values of $k, \\mu$ and $m$ for which\nour algorithm should be used.\n  In the case of non-strict journeys, for which no algorithm is known, we show\nthat a similar strategy can be used to answer the question, still in $O(k\\mu\nn)$ time.\n  Both algorithms gradually build the transitive closure of strict journeys\n($\\mathcal{G}^*_{st}$) or non-strict journeys ($\\mathcal{G}^*$) as the edges\nare examined. A by-product of the execution is to make $\\mathcal{G}^*_{st}$ and\n$\\mathcal{G}^*$ available for further connectivity queries (in a temporal\nversion), these queries being then reduced to simple adjacency tests in a\nstatic graph.\n'
