S'  In this paper, we investigate the anti-Ramsey (more precisely, anti-van der\nWaerden) properties of arithmetic progressions. For positive integers $n$ and\n$k$, the expression $\\mathrm{aw}([n],k)$ denotes the smallest number of colors\nwith which the integers $\\{1,\\ldots,n\\}$ can be colored and still guarantee\nthere is a rainbow arithmetic progression of length $k$. We establish that\n$\\mathrm{aw}([n],3)=\\Theta(\\log n)$ and $\\mathrm{aw}([n],k)=n^{1-o(1)}$ for\n$k\\geq 4$.\n  For positive integers $n$ and $k$, the expression\n$\\mathrm{aw}(\\mathbb{Z}_n,k)$ denotes the smallest number of colors with which\nelements of the cyclic group of order $n$ can be colored and still guarantee\nthere is a rainbow arithmetic progression of length $k$. In this setting,\narithmetic progressions can "wrap around," and $\\mathrm{aw}(\\mathbb{Z}_n,3)$\nbehaves quite differently from $\\mathrm{aw}([n],3)$, depending on the\ndivisibility of $n$. In fact, $\\mathrm{aw}(\\mathbb{Z}_{2^m},3) = 3$ for any\npositive integer $m$. However, for $k\\geq 4$, the behavior is similar to the\nprevious case, that is, $\\mathrm{aw}(\\mathbb{Z}_n,k)=n^{1-o(1)}$.\n'
